questionListItems.title: How can I tell if my Healthier SG SMS is not a scam?

answer.body:
The SMS(es) from MOH's Healthier SG will show the registered sender ID "MOH", in upper case.


We are aware of calls falsely informing recipients that they are from MOH, requesting for your personal or financial information over the phone. Please always verify the authenticity of instructions before offering any personal information. You can also call the MOH Hotline at 6325 9220 if you have any enquiries.

questionListItems.title: If I have a company doctor and/or any other healthcare insurance plans, can I still enrol with a Healthier SG clinic?

answer.body: Your existing health benefits and insurance coverage (e.g., provided by your employer) can co-exist with Healthier SG. MOH encourages employers and insurers to support their panel of clinics to join Healthier SG, so that their employees/clients can tap on medical benefits from employers/insurers and also be supported by the Healthier SG clinic they enrol with for more personalised and comprehensive care offerings.

questionListItems.title: What if my preferred Healthier SG clinic is popular and I am unable to enrol or make my appointment?

answer.body: You can choose to enrol with other Healthier SG clinics suggested in the HealthHub App, or wait for the next available appointment date.

questionListItems.title: What can I redeem my Healthpoints for?

answer.body:
You can redeem your Healthpoints for the following reward types:


  • HPB Credit$

  • HPB & Merchant branded eVouchers

  • Charity Donations

  • SimplyGo eVouchers (Formerly known as TransitLink eVouchers)


You may refer to the rewards section of the Healthy 365 Website at https://go.gov.sg/hpbrewardsfaqs

questionListItems.title: Will I still be entitled to Civil Service medical benefits if I choose to enrol with a GP instead of a polyclinic?

answer.body:
There is no change to a civil servant’s Civil Service medical benefits when he/she is enrolled in Healthier SG.  

 

The annual claim limits, per-visit claim limits and list of subsidised items remain as per the individuals’ prevailing medical schemes. For example, civil servants and pensioners will continue to be subsidised for medical bills incurred at private clinics up to $20/visit, subject to the prevailing co-payment rates and annual claim limits (if any) based on their medical scheme. 

 

Pensioners should continue to refer to the Pensioner’s handbook for details or contact the Pension hotline at 6332 4572 (Mon-Fri 9am to 5pm). For more details, please email Accountant-General's Department (AGD) at agd_mailbox@agd.gov.sg with your query, name, and NRIC number.

questionListItems.title: What are the fully subsidised nationally recommended screenings and vaccinations? How am I eligible?

answer.body:
Nationally recommended screenings listed on the Screen-For-Life (SFL) programme, and vaccinations on the National Adult Immunisation Schedule (NAIS) are fully-subsidised for Healthier SG enrolees who are Singapore Citizens. These must meet the eligibility criteria and are as advised by their family doctor at their enrolled Healthier SG clinic only.


Please see more information and eligibility criteria below:

 

Screen For Life (SFL)

  • Enhanced Screen for Life

  • Screen for Life


National Adult Immunisation Schedule (NAIS)

  • Nationally recommended vaccines

questionListItems.title: What happens if I need to see the doctor for my illness during the same visit for my first Health Plan discussion? Do I still need to pay?

answer.body: The first Health Plan discussion is fully subsidised, and you do not need to pay for the discussion. If you are seeing the doctor for your first Health Plan discussion and for other illnesses, please check with the clinic whether there are charges for consultation/treatment unrelated to Healthier SG.

questionListItems.title: What is the new Healthier SG Chronic Tier and what are the benefits?

answer.body:
From February 2024, CHAS^, Merdeka Generation (MG) and Pioneer Generation (PG) cardholders enrolled to Healthier SG GP clinics with higher chronic medication needs can opt to access a new Healthier SG Chronic Tier.


Specifically, you will have access to selected chronic medications (e.g. for diabetes, high blood pressure), similar to those prescribed and subsidised at polyclinics, at prices comparable to polyclinics.


Cardholders receive help in these two areas:

 

For selected chronic medications – Receive subsidies of up to 87.5% for selected medications with no dollar cap based on the card status.

 

For all services (e.g. consultations, investigations) and other medications – receive subsidies of up to $135 per visit and $360 per year.

 

At every visit, CHAS^/ MG/ PG cardholders can choose to either tap on subsidies under the existing CHAS^ Chronic Tier or the new Healthier SG Chronic Tier.

 

Patients with higher chronic medication needs and bills which exceed the current CHAS^ annual subsidy limits are more likely to benefit.

 

Patients with lower medication needs, may continue to be covered by existing CHAS^ subsidies.

 

You may consult with your family doctor to find out if you are suitable to switch to using the selected chronic medications that are eligible for percentage subsidies under the Healthier SG Chronic Tier.

 

Please note that one subsidy tier may be used at each visit. The remaining dollar subsidy limits will be pro-rated accordingly for the next visit if a different subsidy tier is chosen.

 

Healthier SG benefits and subsidies are available/accessible at your enrolled Healthier SG clinic.

 

^The CHAS Chronic Tier subsidy framework is available for all CHAS cardholders. The Community Health Assist Scheme (CHAS) enables all Singapore Citizens, including Merdeka Generation (MG) and Pioneer Generation (PG) cardholders, to receive subsidies for medical and/or dental care (Only for CHAS Blue/Orange, MG and PG cardholders) at participating General Practitioner (GP) and dental clinics. To find out more about CHAS, please click here.

questionListItems.title: Can I switch doctors/clinic for chronic condition visits and still enjoy subsidies for Healthier SG Chronic Tier?

answer.body:
[Healthier SG Chronic Tier will be available from February 2024] You should enrol with a family doctor that you intend to follow up with for care of all your medical conditions. The benefits you may receive under the Healthier SG Chronic Tier can be used at your enrolled Healthier SG GP clinic.

 

Should you visit another CHAS GP clinic that you are not enrolled with for Healthier SG program, you would be able to access the existing CHAS Chronic Tier subsidies.

questionListItems.title:
How do I enrol if I do not have smartphone? 
Can my caregiver enrol me on his/her HealthHub app?

answer.body:
You can grant access to your family members or loved ones to assist you with the enrolment by adding them as your caregiver in HealthHub and enabling permission to manage Healthier SG on your behalf. You may access the HealthHub app by using your caregiver's smartphone. Your caregiver can then add you as a care recipient to view your health records and manage your e-Services on HealthHub.


You will need your Singpass account to authorise your caregiver via HealthHub. If you do not have a Singpass account, you may register for Singpass through this website or head down to the nearest Singpass counter for assistance, with your caregiver and bring along both your NRICs. For Singpass counter locations, click here.


Follow the steps below to first add a caregiver.

Please ensure that you have enabled "Healthier SG" access in the Caregiver's Details page (as shown in Step 5).


After this has been done, inform your caregiver to add your Health Profile under Add Loved ones, using his/her own HealthHub account.

Once your caregiver has successfully added you as a care recipient, your user profile will be shown on HealthHub for them to assist with your enrolment if you are eligible to enrol in Healthier SG.

Alternatively, you may enrol in Healthier SG through the HealthHub web portal on a computer device and logging in with your Singpass.


HealthHub FAQs can be found here.

questionListItems.title:
I have recently changed my mobile/contact number, how do I update it for Healthier SG?
How do I notify MOH to send my Healthier SG SMSes directly to my caregiver/loved ones, on my behalf?

answer.body:
You may call the MOH Hotline on 6325 9220 or approach our Healthier SG ambassadors at Enrolment Stations for assistance.

 

To check for the nearest location for Healthier SG ambassador’s on-site assistance and operating hours, click here.

questionListItems.title: If I have changed my enrolled clinic, can my current family clinic view my previous Health Plan?

answer.body: Yes, your current family clinic will be able to view your past Health Plans co-developed with your previous family clinic.
You can earn Healthpoints by participating in healthy lifestyle programmes and challenges on the Healthy 365 app.

questionListItems.title: Where can I locate Healthier SG programmes to sign up/participate in?

answer.body:
You will be able to find healthy lifestyle programmes by using the Healthy 365 app:


  • Take healthier actions by getting started with challenges such as the National Steps Challenge and Eat, Drink, Shop Healthy Challenge, participating in recommended programmes (e.g. Live Well, Age Well programme) and booking activities including a wide variety of MOVE IT free exercise classes and health workshop in the community.


  • Earn Healthpoints for taking healthier actions and redeem Healthpoints by choosing from a catalogue of lifestyle rewards available.


  • Track your daily physical activity and sleep duration with a compatible wearable and use the meal log tool to monitor your daily calorie intake under "My Daily Progress" section, which provides a view of your health-related lifestyle data at a glance


  • Enjoy access to informative resources and community partners programmes to support your journey to a healthier lifestyle.

questionListItems.title: What do I need to bring along for my first visit?

answer.body:
Do bring along:

  • your NRIC to your Healthier SG clinic for verification purposes; and

  • your Pioneer Generation/Merdeka Generation and/or Community Health Assist Scheme (CHAS) cards to enjoy the enhanced CHAS subsidies under Healthier SG (effective only from early 2024).


You are strongly encouraged to:

  • bring along prior relevant health screenings, test results and immunisation records (local or overseas) to share with your doctor; and

  • inform your family clinic of your current medications, therapy, or any other medical concerns.
